BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Speaker Series,Religious Studies Speaker Series
DESCRIPTION:Black Sacred Jazz Histories\n \n\nWhat is the social\, cultural
 \, and political authority of Black churches for the people whom these inst
 itutions shaped\, but who chose to pursue their own lives outside of these 
 institutional walls\, without making the leap to other religious traditions
 ? What is authority for those who don’t formally identify with Black church
 es? Jazz is an artistic profession where Black musicians in the era of Jim 
 Crow and within the dominant culture of what was then referred to as the “N
 egro church”—now "the Black church"—viewed themselves as representatives of
  their race. Several musicians also crafted expressions of religion through
  their artistry. This talk will showcase how some prominent jazz artists\, 
 including Duke Ellington and Mary Lou Williams\, agreed with\, or diverged 
 from\, the social and theological norms of Black Protestant church culture 
 through their sacred music\, which also reflected their conceptions of Afri
 can American sacred history.\n\n \n\nPlease register to attend this virtual
  event.
DTEND:20260311T213000Z
DTSTAMP:20260311T170247Z
DTSTART:20260311T200000Z
LOCATION:
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Religious Studies Speaker Series: Vaughn A. Booker
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_52239911805781
URL:https://events.oakton.edu/event/religious-studies-speaker-series-vaughn
 -a-booker
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
CATEGORIES:Arts and Exhibitions
DESCRIPTION:Jack H. Breslow (1927-2023)\, born in New York\, studied at the
  Académie Julian in Paris and the Art Students League in New York City. A p
 rolific studio artist\, Breslow gained recognition for his science fiction 
 book illustrations\, as well as his work on advertising campaigns\, movie p
 osters\, and magazine covers.\n\n \n\nThis exhibition marks the first publi
 c presentation of Breslow’s black-and-white works on paper\, unveiling a se
 ries of fantastical\, metaphysical imagery infused with botanical motifs an
 d expressive rock formations.\n\n \n\nThe Public Reception takes place on T
 hursday\, February 5\, 2026\, 5 - 8 p.m.\n\n \n\nViewings take place from F
 ebruary 5 to March 27\, 2026\, during regular museum hours.
DTSTAMP:20260311T170247Z
DTSTART;VALUE=DATE:20260312
GEO:42.054993;-87.886683
LOCATION:Des Plaines Campus\, Koehnline Museum of Art
SEQUENCE:0
SUMMARY:Jack H. Breslow: Visual Metaphysics in Black and White
UID:tag:localist.com\,2008:EventInstance_50816144479676
URL:https://events.oakton.edu/event/jack-h-breslow-visual-metaphysics-in-bl
 ack-and-white
